<hl>
<seg id=1> Chuan Leekpai: Thailand will hold early general election </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Bangkok integrated news) The Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the night before last that he will hold early general election, while the term of the 7 party coalition government is approaching to an end in Oct. 2001. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> But he also added that the coalition now is in a stable state and capable of carrying out the economic reform program. </seg>
<seg id=4> He said that this kind of economic reform is vitally impartant to the economic recovery and the goal of a sustainable economic growth rate. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Chuan Leekpai observed at the dinner party of the Thai Foreign Correspondent Club:"The confidence of the foreign investors is certainly closely bounded to stable and continuous policies. We will well remember this." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We do not intend to stay until the term is over. </seg>
<seg id=7> We will use as much time as left for us to work on reform our national economy and lay down good fundamentals for the future sustainable development." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leekpai said that he did not decide when to dismiss the congress and hold general election. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand is still troubled by crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> In addition, Chuan Leekpai warned in his speech as well that Thailand was still in crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He made it clear that the current state was still "precarious", the global environment might make Thailand departed from  the goal of turn the declining tendency of the economy in the second half of 1999. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> However, he promised to carry out reform measures in a wider range and put an end to corruption that crippled the national economy of Thailand. </seg>
</p>
